The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro
		 Wednesday, December 24, 2003 				 																				Kalyani Ghosh								Publisher, Thema																																							India is a democracy. If the authors voice is thus stifled, how much of his freedom of expression will be protected? There is a justification for a censor board for films as people react more violently to the audio-visual medium. But words do not wield that power. Moreover, it is possible to judge literary merit, but certainly not what is acceptable and what is not. It is only the reader who can do that. This is also bad for art as this way, fresh points of view will be restricted. We do not want this to be a military state, do we?
